    demo_account_id,
    'session',
    current_session_id,
    'session_client_summary',
    '## What we discussed  
In this session, we explored the recent feelings of anxiety and deep questioning about life that you''ve been experiencing over the past couple of months. You shared how a trip to New York unexpectedly triggered a wave of anxiety and thoughts about how small and insignificant we all might feel in the vastness of the world. This led you into difficult questions about the meaning of life and the reality of death, which you hadn''t fully faced before. We also talked about your personal experiences with loss, especially your close relationship with your grandmother and witnessing her passing. You described how these experiences have shaped your current feelings of loneliness, disconnection, and struggle to find motivation or meaning in daily life. We touched on a vivid dream you had that seems to symbolize your attempts to hide from these overwhelming feelings about death and life.

## What you discovered  
You recognized that although you''ve always known about death, this recent period has brought a new, deeper awareness that feels impossible to ignore or forget. This "knowing" feels heavy and hard to accept, but it also shows your courage in facing a difficult truth. You also noticed your strong sense of empathy, how you naturally think about others'' feelings, and how this has been a meaningful part of who you are. Finally, you identified that your current feelings of disconnection and loneliness might come from this new way of relating to life and death, which is both painful and an important part of your growth.

## Next steps  
Between now and our next session, try to gently notice moments during your day when these heavy thoughts about life and death arise. When you can, allow yourself to sit with these feelings for a few minutes without rushing away, acknowledging that it''s okay to feel uncertain or overwhelmed. Also, continue reflecting on your empathyâ€”observe how your ability to connect with others can be a source of strength, even when you feel isolated. If you feel up to it, jot down any thoughts or feelings that come up during these reflections to bring to our next conversation.

## Gentle reminder  
Remember, it''s natural to feel overwhelmed when facing big questions about life and death. This process takes time, and it''s okay to move slowly. You are showing bravery by opening up to these feelings rather than pushing them away. Each step you take in exploring these thoughts is part of learning how to live more fully, even with uncertainty. Be kind to yourself as you navigate this challenging but meaningful journey.
',
    'en'
  );

